description:
ClickHouse S3 related functions, when not using hive partitioning, supports writing multiple files to the same file path by appending a numbered counter at the end when using `s3_create_new_file_on_insert=1`.
```
create table s3_table (id UInt32) engine=s3(s3_conn, filename='root/file.parquet');
insert into s3_table values 1 SETTINGS s3_create_new_file_on_insert=1;
insert into s3_table values 2 SETTINGS s3_create_new_file_on_insert=1;
select _file, id from s3_table;
"root/file.parquet", 1
"root/file.parquet.1", 2
```
The way this has been implemented is through an in-memory vector keeping the paths produced by this function/ table so that the next insert knows the next filename and upon reading it is possible to enumerate all files. When the server re-starts, this information is lost and ClickHouse relies on a slow retry-mechanism to get the latest inserted file path.
When looking at https://github.com/ClickHouse/ClickHouse/pull/87592, I realized the `StorageObjectStorageConfiguration::getPaths/setPaths` methods are not thread safe. AFAIK, `StorageObjectStorage::write` can be executed in parallel and does not impose any locking mechanism - which might result in the `paths` object being modified simultaneously.
The obivous answer is to add protection around `(get/set)Paths`, but honestly wouldn't it be better if we just deprecated it since [hive partitioning is becoming the default](https://github.com/ClickHouse/ClickHouse/pull/86746)?
The downside tho is that we would no longer support multiple writes to a fixed location without a partition strategy. Actually, it could also break the wildcard partition strategy in case the user is also relying on `s3_create_new_file_on_insert`
